|-
| [[1 Thessalonians]]
| c. 51 CE. One of the earliest of the genuine Pauline epistles.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[2 Thessalonians]]
| c. 51 CE or post-70 CE. If this is a genuine Pauline epistle it follows closely on 1 Thessalonians. But some of the language and theology point to a much later date, from an unknown author using Paul's name.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|92}} (300 CE)
|-
| [[1 Timothy]], [[2 Timothy]], [[Epistle to Titus]]
| c. 100 CE. The two Timothy epistles and Titus reflect a much more developed Church organisation than that reflected in the genuine Pauline epistles.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| [[Codex Sinaiticus]] (350 CE){{Papyrus link|32}} (200 CE)
|-
| [[Paul's Letter to Philemon|Philemon]]
| c. 54–55 CE. A genuine Pauline epistle, written from an imprisonment (probably in Ephesus) that Paul expects will soon be over.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|87}} (3rd century CE)
|-
| [[Letter to the Hebrews|Hebrews]]
| c. 80–90 CE. The elegance of the Greek and the sophistication of the theology do not fit the genuine Pauline epistles, but the mention of Timothy in the conclusion led to its being included with the Pauline group from an early date.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|46}} (late 2nd century or 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[Epistle of James|James]]
| c. 65–85 CE. Like Hebrews, James is not so much a letter as an exhortation; the style of the Greek makes it unlikely that it was actually written by James the brother of Jesus.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|20}}, {{Papyrus link|23}} (early 3rd century CE)
|-
| [[First Peter]]
| c. 75–90 CE{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|72}} (3rd/4th century CE)
|-
| [[Second Peter]]
| c. 110 CE. This is apparently the latest writing in the New Testament, quoting from Jude, assuming a knowledge of the Pauline letters, and including a reference to the gospel story of the [[Transfiguration of Christ]].{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|72}} (3rd/4th century CE)
|-
| [[Epistles of John]]
| 90–110 CE.{{sfn|Kim|2003|p=250}} The letters give no clear indication, but scholars tend to place them about a decade after the Gospel of John.{{sfn|Kim|2003|p=250}}
| {{Papyrus link|9}}, [[Uncial 0232]], [[Codex Sinaiticus]] (3rd/4th century CE)
|-
| [[Epistle of Jude|Jude]]
| Uncertain. The references to "brother of James" and to "what the apostles of our Lord Jesus Christ foretold" suggest that it was written after the apostolic letters were in circulation, but before 2 Peter, which uses it.{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|72}} (3rd/4th century CE)
|-
| [[Book of Revelation|Revelation]]
| c. 95 CE. The date is suggested by clues in the visions pointing to the reign of the emperor [[Domitian]].{{sfn|Perkins|2012|p=19ff}}
| {{Papyrus link|98}} (150–200 CE)
|}

