{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Use Australian English|date=October 2016}} '''Oliver Feltham''' is an [[Australian]] [[philosopher]]<ref>[http://consc.net/tree.html Australasian Philosophy Family Tree]</ref> and [[translation|translator]] working in [[Paris, France]]. He is known primarily for his English translations of [[Alain Badiou]], most notably Badiou’s [[Masterpiece|magnum opus]] ''Being and Event'' (2006).<ref>[http://ndpr.nd.edu/review.cfm?id=15526 Review of ''Alain Badiou: Live Theory''] reviewed by [[Todd May]]</ref> Feltham's own writings are drawn from many of his research interests including [[Marxism]], [[critical theory]], and the history of [[metaphysics]]. His recent work has also focused on [[psychoanalysis]] and [[Jaques Lacan]].
Feltham received his [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] at the [[University of Sydney]]. In 2000, he completed his doctoral thesis at [[Deakin University]] in [[Melbourne, Australia|Melbourne]], writing his dissertation on the [[ontology|ontological]] distinction between [[praxis (process)|praxis]] and work in ancient and modern philosophy (with a focus on Badiou and [[Michel Foucault]]) based on research Feltham conducted in Paris.<ref name="faculty homepage">[http://www.aup.edu/faculty/dept/clen/feltham.htm Faculty Homepage]</ref>
Feltham teaches at the [[American University of Paris]] (AUP) where he has been since 2004 and where he became a full-time [[associate professor]] in 2006, teaching in the [[comparative literature]] and "Global Communications" departments and in the Philosophy Program. Feltham is also a researcher at the ''Circle for Lacanian Ideology Critique'' at the [[Jan van Eyck Academie]] in [[Maastricht]].<ref name="faculty homepage"/>
