{{Use British English|date=August 2011}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}} {{Infobox person | name = Philip Jourdain | image = <!-- NOTE TO EDITORS: Do not replace the header image unless it is with a photo under a public domain or free license (NOT the same as fair use). Any fair use photos (i.e. promotional photos, album covers) are copyright violations and will be deleted. Also see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Non-free content use criteria --> | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = 16 October 1879 | birth_place = [[Ashbourne, Derbyshire|Ashbourne]], [[Derbyshire]] | death_date = {{d-da|1 October 1919|16 October 1879}} | death_place = [[Crookham Village|Crookham]],<!--This is according to the ''MacTutor History of Mathematics archive''. However, [[Ivor Grattan-Guinness]] gives [[Fleet, Hampshire]] in ''Writing the history of mathematics'', edited by Joseph Warren Dauben and Christoph J. Scriba, 2002.--> [[Hampshire]] | education = | occupation = Editor and mathematician | spouse = Laura Jourdain | parents = Emily Clay and Francis Jourdain | children = }}
'''Philip Edward Bertrand Jourdain''' (16 October 1879 – 1 October 1919) was a British [[logician]] and follower of [[Bertrand Russell]].
He was born in [[Ashbourne, Derbyshire|Ashbourne]] in Derbyshire<ref>*{{MacTutor Biography|id=Jourdain}}</ref> one of a large family belonging to Emily Clay and his father Francis Jourdain (who was the vicar at Ashbourne).<ref name=turn/> He was partly disabled by [[Friedreich's ataxia]]. He corresponded with [[Georg Cantor]] and [[Gottlob Frege]], and took a close interest in the paradoxes related to [[Russell's paradox]], formulating the [[card paradox]] version of the [[liar paradox]].<ref name=turn>[http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Biographies/Jourdain.html Turnbull archive] accessed 7 December 2007</ref> He corresponded with [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]], meeting with him in Cambridge to discuss Frege's book [[Grundgesetze der Arithmetik]], of parts of which Jourdain had prepared a translation. He also worked on [[algebraic logic]], and the [[history of science]] with [[Isaac Newton]] as a particular study. He was London editor for ''[[The Monist]]''. Near the end of his life he became increasingly obsessed by trying to prove the [[axiom of choice]], and published several incorrect proofs of it. {{harvtxt|Littlewood|1986|loc=p.129}} describes Jourdain on his deathbed still arguing with him about his (incorrect) proof of the axiom of choice.
His sister [[Eleanor Jourdain]] was an English academic and author. Another sister, Margaret (1876-1951), was an authority on the history of fine English home-furnishings, and the life-long companion of the novelist Ivy Compton-Burnett.
==Works== The following works of Philip Jourdain are available from [[Internet Archive]]: * 1908: [https://archive.org/details/jstor-27900104 Some Points in the Foundation of Mathematical Physics] in [[The Monist]] v 18 * 1911: [https://archive.org/details/jstor-27900347 Some Modern Advances in Logic] in ''The Monist'' v 21 * 1913: [https://archive.org/details/thenatureofmath00jouruoft The Nature of Mathematics] * 1913: [https://archive.org/details/jstor-27900429 The Nature and Validity of the Principle of Least Action] in ''The Monist'' v 23 * 1914: [https://archive.org/details/jstor-27900477 The Economy of Thought] in ''The Monist'' v 24 * 1918: [https://archive.org/details/philosophyrussel00jouruoft The Philosophy of B*rtr*nd R*ss*ll with an appendix of leading passages from certain other works] * 1919: [https://archive.org/details/jstor-27900767 Indefinables and Indemonstrables in Mathematics and Theology] in ''The Monist'' v 29 Jordain acted as editor for *1914: [[Augustus De Morgan]]: [https://archive.org/details/cu31924012316901 Essays on the Life and Work of Newton] Jourdain made the following translations: * 1911: [[Ernst Mach]] [https://archive.org/details/historyandrootp00machgoog History and Root of the Principle of Conservation of Energy] * 1915: Ernst Mach [https://archive.org/details/scienceofmechani00machrich The Science of Mechanics] * 1915: [[Georg Cantor]] [https://archive.org/details/contributionstof00cantrich Contributions to the Foundation of the Theory of Transfinite Numbers]
