{{Infobox philosopher | region = [[Western philosophy]] | era = [[Contemporary philosophy]] | image = | caption = | name = Ray Monk | birth_date = {{bda|1957|2|df=yes|15}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | institutions = [[University of Southampton]] | school_tradition = [[Analytic philosophy]], [[postanalytic philosophy]] | main_interests = [[Logic]], [[philosophy of language]], [[philosophy of mathematics]], [[history of analytic philosophy]] | influences = [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]] | influenced = | notable_ideas = }}
'''Ray Monk''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSL}} (born 15 February 1957) is a British philosopher. He is Emeritus Professor at the [[University of Southampton]], where he taught from 1992<ref>https://www.southampton.ac.uk/philosophy/about/staff/rm.page</ref> to 2018.<ref>https://twitter.com/Raymodraco/status/1024230159556206592</ref>
He won the [[John Llewellyn Rhys Prize]] and the 1991 [[Duff Cooper Prize]] for his biography of [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]], ''Ludwig Wittgenstein: The Duty of Genius''. His interests lie in the philosophy of mathematics, the [[history of analytic philosophy]], and philosophical aspects of biographical writing. His biography of [[Robert Oppenheimer]] was published in 2012.
Since 2012 he has contributed to the ''[[New Statesman]]'', contributing articles on philosophy and [[veganism]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/writers/318837|title=Writers|website=www.newstatesman.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-01}}</ref>
In 2015 he was awarded a Fellowship by the [[Royal Society of Literature]].<ref>http://rsliterature.org/fellows/current-fellows/</ref>
==Works== *''Ludwig Wittgenstein: The Duty of Genius''. London: Vintage, 1991. *''Bertrand Russell: The Spirit of Solitude 1872–1921''. London: Vintage, 1996. *''Russell''. London: Weidenfeld & Nicolson, 1997. *''Bertrand Russell: The Ghost of Madness 1921–1970''. London: Vintage, 2001. *''How to Read Wittgenstein''. London: Granta, 2005. *''Inside the Centre: the Life of J. Robert Oppenheimer''. London: Jonathan Cape, 2012 *"Ludwig Wittgenstein: A Sketch of His Life" (chapter in ''A Companion to Wittgenstein'', edited by [[Hans-Johann Glock]] and [[John Hyman (philosopher)|John Hyman]]. Wiley-Blackwell, 2017)
